Incredibly lucky and thankful to be surrounded by so many amazing people who spent this weekend showering me with love, surprises, and who continually push me to be my best self. This weekend was one of many firsts; my first surprise birthday dinner, first comedy show, first time to the springs in Florida and it’s safe to say my last year in my 20’s is off to a great start. Thank you to everyone for the birthday wishes, everyone I shared this weekend with, and everyone I will share this year with. Here’s to more firsts, more adventures, and many more memories with my people. 💚

Today, I find myself laying by my best friend’s pool with tears in my eyes bc I cannot believe the gift the universe just gave me.

This past week has been a tough one for me mentally & emotionally. I’ve shared my journey with mental health with you all many times over the years but it’s been a while since we talked. 

Last year I went through a tough break up & found myself turning a little too heavily towards alcohol so to save myself from further harm, I gave it up. Around that same time, my therapist & I both agreed it would benefit me to seek out medication (Lexapro) in adjunct to therapy.

The idea of sobriety was initially introduced to me by a girl who also sent me this book: Untamed by Glennon Doyle. Over the past year, I’ve chipped away at it chapter by chapter. Today, however, after a long emotional week, a week where I’ve again reconsidered my relationship with alcohol, & a week where my anxiety & depression have fought to get the best of me, I opened up the book to where I last left off, on these exact pages. ➡️

Idk what force was at play here, the universe, God, karma… I could have finished this book a long time ago, I could have never even met the girl who gave me the book, but for whatever reason, I was destined to stumble upon this chapter today of all days. I can’t get over the synchronicities leading up to this moment. All I know is I needed to read these words today & maybe you do too.

Mental illness robbed me of so many years of my life: convincing me I was crazy, I was alone, I didn’t matter, I was unlovable & all because I didn’t know other people were also struggling with the same thing & there was help out there. While there are still days or weeks that are harder than others, it’s nothing compared to how I struggled in the past and I stand by the fact that idk how I survived the first 28 years of my life without therapy, medication, & just the simple knowledge that I wasn’t alone in this fight. (cont’d)
